<dl id="n56124f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56124f">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56124f"> 124(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> in the days of yore / &amp; in times long gone / before there was a / King <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56124f"><li>FW 359.24f </li><li><a href="../../flex/mf/lexmf.htm#n56124f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/mf/l39mf.htm#n56124f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56124f">MS BL 47480.248v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:382 <a name="mfd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mfd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/mf/mfd5.htm#n56124f">Draft: II.3&sect;6.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">I have been careful to preserve the balanced sentences with which the tales open; the tautology and the prose-rhythm serving to attract attention, <i>e.g.</i> &ldquo;<mark>In days of yore and in times long gone before there was a King</mark>,&rdquo; etc.; in England where we strive not to waste words this becomes &ldquo;Once upon a time.&rdquo; <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE4" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE4"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 162</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
